{"/service/ndnp/mnhi/batch_mnhi_mazda_ver01/data/sn90059180/00212479664/1913082201/0422.xml":{"full_text":"i*\ni*\nilir\nik\nHi\niH\nith\ndii\nOr\ntt\nHi\nib\nill\nVfc\ntt\nifc\nifc\niti\ntf\n\u2022I#\nWK RETAIL BAGGAGE\nI At wholesale prices\nFor the\nGRAND OPENING\nof our\nNEW\nWe will carry a complete line of\nFurniture, rugs and\ncarpets, hardware,\ndry goods, ladies' and\nchildren's coats and.\nsuits, men's and boys'\nsuits and furnishings,\nladies,' children's and\nmen's shoes and\ngroceries\nTHE LARGEST STORE\nON THE RANGE\nDONT FORGET THE PLACE\nKETOLA&CO.\n\"Your Money's Worth or Your Money Bach\"\nCor. Mesaba Ave. Pine St.\nVIRGINIA, MINN.\nDuluth, Missabe Northern Ry.\nThree Fast Trains Daily Between Virginia 6 Duluth\n7:30 a.m.\nLEAVE VIR6INIA 12:27 p.m.\n4:30 p.m.\n7:40 a.m.\n3:50 p.m.\n7:58 p.m.\nLEAVE DULUTH\nTrain leaving at 4:30 p. m. provides fast through service\ncarrying Cafe Observation car, meals served a la carte.\nClose connections made at Duluth with trains for Twin\nCities, Chicago and Eastern points. For rates and other in\u00ad\nformation call at D. M.& N. passenger station or by phone No. 28.\nTHE TRU8K FACTORY\n-OF DULUTH- (3\nNORTHERN TRUNK CO.\n22S Wf\u00bbt Fir*t St.\nWrite for our catalogue\nDrop in and look around\n.We know we can please you\nMtei Hope Seibold, B. M.\n'w* Teacher of\n1 PI AN\u00a9 AND ORGAN\nPhono 718 405 Cedar St\nVIRGINIA\nJir\nTHE\n10:31 a.m.\nARRIVE DULUTH 3:21p.m.\n6:46 p.m.\n10:32 a.m.\nARRIVE VIR6INIA 6:50 p.m.\n10:22 p.m.\nH. W. BROWN,\" Agent.\nION DRUG STORE\nQuality Drugs, Corteous Ser\nvice\u2014A purchase will con\n\u2022ince you.\n226 CHESTNUT PHONE 777\nOPPOSITE ORMONDE HOTEL\nMISS VIVIAN PERRY\nTeacher of\nChina Painting.\nHand Painted China For Sale\nHughs* Hotel\n203 Lake Blvd.\nPhone 683\nVIRGINIA\nPOSITION WANTED\nA position in an office* book*\nkeeping or typewriting by young\nlady with experience.\nAddress 308 Birch St. Chisholm.\n\u2022it'-*,\nFounded February JO, 1898,\nby W. B. Hannaford\nPubllehedby\nTil Eitirprisi Priitiig ill PuMsliig Go.\nEntered at the Poet Office at Virginia, Min\u00ad\nnesota, as second class mail matter\nSubscription Price $2.00 per year in advance\nHarry Thaw is again in the lime\u00ad\nlight. Thaw's escape from the New\nYork hospital for the criminal insane\nhas been one of the sensations of the.\nweek. Harry Thaw is to be pitied.\nHe never had a chance. Reared in an\natmosphere of pampered wealth he\nnever brought to maturity a man's\nperspective. He is just as unfortun\u00ad\nate as the city street waif who never\ngets a chance, while he is the product\nof the social extreme. Thaw murder\ned a man in cold blood. He believed\nhimself justified. His trial on' the\nmurder charge was one of the most\nsordid stories ever written into print.\nHis case has been constantly before\nthe public for the past three years,\npractically. It has furnished a start\u00ad\nling example of the far-fetched ends\nthe law may be made to serve. Every\nknown process and a liberal use of\nmoney has been invoked to secure his\nrelease, but all have failed. If Thaw\ndeserves liberty at all he deserves it\nlegitimately, and if it is true that he\ncannot be tpken back to Matteawan it\nis just another demonstration of the\nfact that the law is sometimes fear\u00ad\nfully and wonderfully made.\n\u2014O\nExecutive Agent Rider, of the state\ngame and fish commission, has been a\nvisitor on the range within the week.\nMr. Rider met a good many people\nand all did what they could to impress\nhim with the fact that better protec\ntion for game and fish in this sec\ntion of the state is much desired.\nThere has been something of a shake\nup in the commission during the past\nmonth, and it is hoped it will have a\ngood effect on the situation generally.\nAbove everything else, however, one\nthing stands out northern Minnesota\nis not getting the attention it deserves\nfrom the state game and fish commis\u00ad\nsion. It is perhaps true that the ad\u00ad\nministrative department is hampered\nby a lack of. funds. However, it\nwould appear that the better thing to\ndo would be to put more of the game\nwardens in the southern section of the\nstate on a reward basis and have more\nof the salaried men stationed in this\nsection, which most of all needs the\nprotection of capable wardens for the\nconservation of its game and fish.\n0\nReviling Socialists and Socialism is\nthe fashion with a good many people\nwho have slight idea what they are\ntalking about but evidently feel that\nit is necessary to make some kind of a\nnoise. Thinking people do not revile\nsocialism. It is one of the most pow\u00ad\nerful of present day influences it is\none of the most beautiful theories that\nhas ever been advanced through the\nmedium of political propaganda. A\ngood many will never espouse the doc\u00ad\ntrines of socialism for the simple rea\u00ad\nson that they do not believe them\npractical, and there is little practical\nprecedent to prove the contrary. The\nsocialists have a good many extrem\nists in their ranks, but after all they\nare a wholesome influence in present\nday politics and whether we agree\nwith them or not it is well always to\nremember that the other fellow has a\nviewpoint to which he is entitled and\nin which, while he may be mistaken,\nhe may also be very sincere.\n0\nIt is becoming the popular thing to\ndo with the delegates to the numerous\nnational conventions that meet in Du\u00ad\nluth during the summer to make aside\ntrip to the ranges. Virginia has been\ngetting somo .fine advertising this\nyear in that way. The hotel men and\nthe railroad men are coming this week\nand Virginia people have nothing to\nlose by sending them away with the\nimpression that in addition to this be\u00ad\ning the liveliest town in the northwest\nit is also one of the most hospitable.\nThe local officials of the Canadian\nNorthern, the Cfmmercial Club offi\u00ad\ncers and others are doing a good deal\nto advertise Virginia in this way and\ntheir efforts are generally appreciat\u00ad\ned. And one of these days Virginia\nmight land a national convention for\nherself.\nThe annual report of the state fire\nmarshal is at hand, and contains some\nhighly interesting figures on fire\nlosses. One thing is very noticeable,\nand that is the number of fires of in\u00ad\ncendiary origin. The report is also\ninteresting as indicating the obstacles\nunder which the state fire marshal\nworks in arresting and convicting in\u00ad\ncendiaries. The state fire marshal's\ndepartment is worth every cent-that it\ncosts Minnesota, as its sixth annual\nreport will amply demonstrate. Fire\nlosses have been decreased 33 1-3 per\ncent in Minnesota during the past\nyear and the co-operation of the peo\npie of the state with the department\nas well as its prompt and active inter\u00ad\nest have largely contributed to that\ncondition.\nO\nNate Collier, for some time con-\nnected with the Duluth News Tribune,\nwhere he contributed the feature \"lit\u00ad\ntle Dope on the Side,\" is now the Car\u00ad\ntoonist of the Chicago Daily Journal.\nNate made'a good many, friends while\nin the newspaper game m, Minnesota,\nand they will all be glad to know that\nhis work is going fine on the Journal.\nCollier brings to the business fine abil-\nJ\"\ntFhe Enterprise' acknowledges an in\u00ad\nvitation to the second annual agricul\u00ad\ntural exhibit of th4 Bear River Farm\u00ad\ner's Club, which is io be held at Bear\nRiver post-office hext Monday and\nTuesday, -An automobile trip to Bear\nRiver is well worth while to anybody\nwho has the time Knd the automobile.\nThe Bear' -River folk, too,, are ideal\nhosts and their exhibit last year was\nworth traveling along distance to see\nand this year's is going to be super\u00ad\nior in every respeet:\nSt: fouis county's big annual agri\u00ad\ncultural show will the held at Hibbing\nnext week. The fair this year is go\u00ad\ning- to eclipse and outshine all previ\u00ad\nous fairs and Virginia people are go\u00ad\ning to attend it in numbers and are\ngoing to get some surprises when they\nsee the things that are doing in an\nagricultural way indicated by the\nfair exhibits.\nBetter laws are desirable, but the\nthing most sections of the country\nneeds is better citizens. The man who\ndoesn't take an interest in the affairs\nof his town, and if he thinks they are\nnot being properly handled doesn't\nget up and say so, is about the last\nperson in the world who ought to talk\nabout \"better laws.\"\nHuerta claims he should be \"rec\u00ad\nognized\" according to current news\ndispatches, and Huerta is right. He\nshould have been recognized some\ntime ago as a person utterly unfit for\nthe responsibilities delegated to him\nas the executive head of the Mexican\ngovernment.\nTo say that Governor Eberhart has\nthe right hunch on the public utili\u00ad\nties bill is merely giving the devil his\ndues.\nThis has been a week of peace that\npasseth understanding in Virginia.\nExchange Comments\nGrand Rapids Herald-Review:\u2014St.\nLouis county is to vote soon on a\nproposition to expend $10,000,000 on\nroads. Our neighbor has also dis\u00ad\ncovered the folly of attempting a\nroad program piece-meal.\nMesaba Ore:\u2014The heavy fine im\u00ad\nposed on a young man who deliberate\u00ad\nly picked a fight on the street was\nwell warranted, but an even surer\nway to stop these ready mixers would\nbe a straight jail sentence. Street\nbrawls aro unwholesome Advertising\nany city, and the, authorities should\nuse every method to stamp uot their\ntoo frequent occurrence.\nBiwabik Times:\u2014The decision in\nthe case of the Lake Superior Tax\nassociation vs. the Ely city official was\nneeded. It will bring about more re\u00ad\nspect for the law. It may result in\nles public improvements, but in the\nend put the towns on a more substan\u00ad\ntial footing. It was false economy to\nfiigure that any expense was justified\nas long as the mining companies had\nto foot the bill. We believe a differ\nnt policy should have been adopted\nin the past and will have to be pursu\u00ad\ned in the future.\nNashwauk HeraldDynamiting\nfor fish seems to be a popular sport\nwith some brainless, good for nothing\nreptiles masquerading as men. A\nparty of dynamiters were seen at\nBuck lake last Sunday and while they\nwere scared away they were success\u00ad\nful in shooting several shots. The\nparty was watched and they head\u00ad\ned for Stevenson which seems to be\npopular hangout for this class\nwhich is the scum of society. Game\nWarden Woods has ben notified and\nwill attempt to bring the guilty ones\nbefore eourt. A man low and mean\nenough to dynamite a lake for the\nsake of a few fish is not worthy the\nrice of a stick of dynamite to blow\nhim off the earth.\nAurora News:\u2014Concrete roadways\nare coming into favor throughout the\nentire country and it is predicted that\nwithin a few years the main thorough\u00ad\nfares of travel betwen important\ncities or centers of population will be\nbuilt of this material. To date\nthe main objection that has been ad\u00ad\nvanced is-theinitial cost of installa\u00ad\ntion. This amounts to considerable\nwhen compared with dirt and gravel\nroadwayss. However, when the cost\nof maintenance is compared the fig\u00ad\nures all are in favor of the concrete\nroadway. The money saved, in five\nyears on repairing will in most in\u00ad\nstances pay for the more permanent\nroadway. The. objection to the hard\nsurface has been overcome by a cov\u00ad\nering of tar, or other elastic substance\nwhich can de replaced at small cost.\nThe glare of the. concrete can be over\u00ad\ncome by mixing/a dark coloring mat\u00ad\nter Into the surface coat. Recently\nthere has ben some agitation to have\nthe roads betwen the range cities and\nvillages made ^of this material as\nfast as the surfoce of the present\nroads need repairing. There is also\nagitation for a concrete roadway be\ntween the ranges and Duluth. We\nbelieve that the mater should be care\u00ad\nfully Considered by the county and\ntownship boards, and if deemed prac\u00ad\ntical, a start in- this direction made\nnext spring wben new road work is\nundertaken.\n'it\nWN HOSE\nWA TER/NG POTS\nHAMMOCKS\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK IN THE\nEAST IS OPTIMISTIC\nS. M. Lippman, of the Minnesota\nDry Goods Company, returned Mon\u00ad\nday evening from a two weeks buying\ntrip to the east, during which he\nvis\u00ad\nited New York, Boston and a number\nof other eastern cities. Mr. Lippman\nsays that the business outlook in the\neast from the standpoint of the whole\u00ad\nsalers is optimistic,-and the prospect\nof tariff revision seems to have no ef\u00ad\nfect on trade. Garment makers and\nfactories contributing to the stocks\nof the dry goods and ready-to-wear\ntrade are rushed with orders ana\nwholesalers generally express satis\u00ad\nfaction with conditions. Mr. Lippman\nbought new stocks for the Virginia\nstore. They will be here and opened\nin a few weeks and there will be a fine\nshowing of seasonable fall and winter\nstyles at the Minnesota shortly.\nAre Yotf Looking for a\nGood Investment\nSee MARTIN NELSON\nFor Chestnut street prop\u00ad\nerty and residence prop\u00ad\nerty and lota.\nTimber Farm Lands\nand Improved Farms\nOffice 222 Chestnut Street\nTelephone No. 499\nVmm Cm* Hmv Ymmr\nOld Carpets\nDy4am4Wmvwm tmtm\nNew Rugs\n\u2022t\na saving\nof half the cost of or\u00ad\ndinary rags. By improved methods\nwhich it owns\nexclusively, the Olson\nRag Company, of Chicago, makes\nbeautiful rags\u2014totally dif\nferent and far superior to\nJr. other rugs woven from\nold carpets.\nVim*\nColem For VMPMMV\nLet me show yon the many beautiful patterns\nfrom which yon can select, plain, fancy, orna*\nmental\u2014fit tor any parlor. These rags are re\n\u2022eraiWe\u00bb bright and durable\u2014woven in 12 colors\nand 29 sizes\u2014large and small\u2014without seams.\nGuaranteed to wear 10 years. Every order com*\nDieted within three days.\nYour old carpets are worth money, no matter\nhow badly worn. Dont throw them away. Write\nme a postal or telephone me, and I will call with\nsamples, book of designs, prices and complete\ninformation abont tbtt good mooey-eaving op*\nport unity.\nR. T. Colbath, Agent\n709 .4th ST. NORTH SIDE. VIRGINIA\n510 Washington Street\nPhone No. 488\nHIBBING, MINN.\nW. A. McKenzie\nHOUSES RAISED, LOWERED\nMOVED AND REPAIRED\nROOFS RAISED AND RKPAIRID\nSMOKE STACKS RAISED\nHotel Mitchell\nPhono No. 192\nVIRGINIA, MINN.\nFirst sale of. cottage\nsites, Sand Lake, be\u00ad\nin a\nPrices will be raised\n25 percent on Septem\nber See announce\nment elsewhere in thU\nissue^-s^\n\"WOW\" ISN'T IT HOT?\nSome of our relief balm for this hot\nweather is as follows:\nREFRtGERA\nTORS\n/CE CREAM FREEZERS\nLEMOM SQUEEZERS\ntCER/CKS\nLA\nothers.\nDon cook on\nrange.\ncne uhgiMa fiardware eo.\nB. 3. George, lt)\u00abr.\nWe Sell Everything in Hardware.\nVise either a kero\u00ad\nsene, gasoline or\nalcohol stove.\nWe sell em.\nJust a Few Words\nOf Advice\nfrom his banker has helped many a man to establish\nhimself firmly on the financial ladder. Why not\nput yourself in position to get this help in case of\nneed? No expense, just open an account with\nbank- No account too large or too small to\nthe personal attention of our officers. Their exper\u00ad\nience in financial affairs has been long and Varied,\nthey know the strong points which won for success\u00ad\nful men\u2014the weak points which brought failure to\nGood Roads For\nTolophoio Talk\nThe rood roads movement has not been confined to\nthe highways. Everywhere the Bell Telephone has\ncovered the country with \"good roads\" for tele\u00ad\nphone talk.\nThere are 13 million miles of these \"good tele\u00ad\nphone, roads\" in the Bell System, running hundreds\nand thousands of miles, connecting industrial and\ncommercial centers everywhere.\nLong Distance Bell Telephone\nLines Reach Nearly Everywhere.\nair\u2014MTC.\nworld bat there Is\nqaattty abou